title: For Sale/Trade:  Belgian Browning SA-22 taledown
postcontent: Belgian made Browning SA-22 with a Leupold scope mount and a Simmons 4x scope.  This is the real deal - it is an authentic Belgian made SA-22 in excellent condition, straight out of the fifties and accurate.  There are Japanese SA-22 rifles currently produced, and they are probably fine rifles, but this rifle is Belgian and nolonger in production.  These slick little rifles are among the first few original "take-down" designs, back before the current resurgence of rimfire rifle takedown popularity.  The novelty of its unique design and its famously solid lock-up are a couple of the reasons for my original interest in it.  I woud add another $130 to the price with the Leupold scope mount, steel 1" rings (solid stuff), and inexpensive (yet impressive) Simmons 4x scope - it is a sweet little outfit as it is.  I would listen to any REASONABLE offer. rifle - $850scope - $50mount & rings - $80 (Leupold, steel)***************************************************************************I am currently interested in acquiring a Rossi Ranch Hand and I would give partial trade value for one in decent condition.  If given the option, I would prefer the .38/.357 model over all others.

title: For Sale:  NIB Czechpoint CSA Vz.58 Military 7.62x39mm Rifle Czech Import Milled VZ58 CZ58 CZ AK47 VZ2008 2008
postcontent: Up for auction is a factory new & original Czech Vz.58 Sporter rifle, chambered for the popular 7.62x39mm round. This is a Czechpoint-USA import made by C.S.A., so it has all Czech parts. This includes the receiver, internals, and furniture. Rifle is 100% new, as received from the importer this December. It comes with 2 high cap magazines, sling, and more. In 1958 after years of development, the prototype SA.58 was put through extensive testing. It had a milled receiver, with many lightening cuts and streamlined for mass production. It fired using a striker system, which allowed it to be more compact and reliable. Its bolt locked into the receiver using a falling wedge or block, not unlike that used in the German P.38 pistol. It operated with a short-stroke gas piston, which was very similar to the one used in the FN FAL. It fed from curved magazines made of a lightweight but durable aluminium alloy, which held 30 rounds. Eventually after a few more small tweeks and changes, it was adopted as the Samopal Vzor 58. This made Czechoslovakia the only Warsaw Pact nation not to adopt some variation of the AK47 or AKM. The Vz.58, like the Vz.52 before it, was its own unique design. It had a milled receiver, but was still lighter than even a stamped Russian AKM at only 6.4 lbs. It was very compact too. title: For Sale:  NIB Czechpoint CSA Vz.58 Military 7.62x39mm Rifle Czech Import Milled VZ58 CZ58 CZ AK47 VZ2008 2008
postcontent: Up for auction is a factory new & original Czech Vz.58 Sporter rifle, chambered for the popular 7.62x39mm round. This is a Czechpoint-USA import made by C.S.A., so it has all Czech parts. This includes the receiver, internals, and furniture. Rifle is 100% new, as received from the importer this December. It comes with 2 high cap magazines, sling, and more. In 1958 after years of development, the prototype SA.58 was put through extensive testing. It had a milled receiver, with many lightening cuts and streamlined for mass production. It fired using a striker system, which allowed it to be more compact and reliable. Its bolt locked into the receiver using a falling wedge or block, not unlike that used in the German P.38 pistol. It operated with a short-stroke gas piston, which was very similar to the one used in the FN FAL. It fed from curved magazines made of a lightweight but durable aluminium alloy, which held 30 rounds. Eventually after a few more small tweeks and changes, it was adopted as the Samopal Vzor 58. This made Czechoslovakia the only Warsaw Pact nation not to adopt some variation of the AK47 or AKM. The Vz.58, like the Vz.52 before it, was its own unique design. It had a milled receiver, but was still lighter than even a stamped Russian AKM at only 6.4 lbs. It was very compact too. It measured just over 33" long, with a 15.4" barrel. It had a 14x1mm threaded muzzle and took a detaching blade bayonet. Everything about it was designed to be slim and lightweight.
